<p>The <b>automotive industry</b> comprises a wide range of <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Company" title=3D"Company">companies</a> and <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Organization" title=3D"Organization">o=
rganizations</a> involved in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/D=
esign" title=3D"Design">design</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Business_development" title=3D"Business development">development</a>, <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Manufacturing" title=3D"Manufacturing=
">manufacturing</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marketing" ti=
tle=3D"Marketing">marketing</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S=
elling" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Selling">selling</a>, <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maintenance" title=3D"Maintenance">repairing</a>=
, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Custom_car" title=3D"Custom =
car">modification</a> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Motor_veh=
icle" title=3D"Motor vehicle">motor vehicles</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_1-0=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Automotive_i=
ndustry#cite_note-:0-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Automotive_industry#cite_note-=
2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup> It is one of the world's largest <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Industry_(economics)" title=3D"Industry (economics)">industrie=
s</a> by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Revenue" title=3D"Revenue=
">revenue</a> with global automotive market at ~$2.75 trillion in 2025. <su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Automotive_industry#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The word <i>automotive</i> comes from the <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Greek_language" title=3D"Greek language">Greek</a> <i>autos<=
/i> (self), and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Latin" title=3D"La=
tin">Latin</a> <span title=3D"Latin-language text"><i lang=3D"la">motivus</=
i></span> (of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Motion" title=3D"Mot=
ion">motion</a>), referring to any form of self-powered vehicle. This term,=
 as proposed by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elmer_Ambrose_Sper=
ry" title=3D"Elmer Ambrose Sperry">Elmer Sperry</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-STS_=
of_US_4-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aut=
omotive_industry#cite_note-STS_of_US-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"noprint Inl=
ine-Template" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Verifiability" title=3D"Wikipedia:Verifiability"><s=
pan title=3D"Quotation needed from source to verify. (October 2018)">need q=
uotation to verify</span></a></i>]</sup> (1860=E2=80=931930), first came in=
to use to describe automobiles in 1898.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-5" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Automotive_industry#cite_no=
te-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup>
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DAutomotive_industry&am=
p;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edit=
</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article=
: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_the_automobile" title=
=3D"History of the automobile">History of the automobile</a></div><figure c=
lass=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/File:Thomas_B_Jeffery_Works_Drawing.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-d=
escription"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thum=
b/0/06/Thomas_B_Jeffery_Works_Drawing.jpg/250px-Thomas_B_Jeffery_Works_Draw=
ing.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"145" class=3D"mw-file-e=
lement" data-file-width=3D"690" data-file-height=3D"400"></a><figcaption>Th=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_B._Jeffery_Company" title=
=3D"Thomas B. Jeffery Company">Thomas B. Jeffery Company</a> automobile fac=
tory in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kenosha,_Wisconsin" title=
=3D"Kenosha, Wisconsin">Kenosha, Wisconsin</a>, around 1916</figcaption></f=
igure>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Workers_in_Fiat_factories,_Turin.jpg" class=
=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia=
/commons/thumb/a/a1/Workers_in_Fiat_factories%2C_Turin.jpg/250px-Workers_in=
_Fiat_factories%2C_Turin.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"23=
9" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"950" data-file-height=3D"90=
8"></a><figcaption><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fiat_1800_and_2=
100" title=3D"Fiat 1800 and 2100">Fiat 1800 and 2100</a> sedans being assem=
bled at a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fiat" title=3D"Fiat">Fia=
t</a> factory in 1961</figcaption></figure>
<p>The automotive industry began in the 1860s with hundreds of manufacturer=
s pioneering the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brass_Era_car" ti=
tle=3D"Brass Era car">horseless carriage</a>. Early car manufacturing invol=
ved manual assembly by a human worker. The process evolved from engineers w=
orking on a stationary car to a conveyor belt system where the car passed t=
hrough multiple stations of more specialized engineers. In the 1960s, robot=
ic equipment was introduced, and most cars are now mainly assembled by auto=
mated machinery.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Automotive_industry#cite_note-6"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>For many decades, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Autom=
otive_industry_in_the_United_States" title=3D"Automotive industry in the Un=
ited States">United States</a> led the world in total automobile production=
, with the U.S. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_Three_(automob=
ile_manufacturers)" title=3D"Big Three (automobile manufacturers)">Big Thre=
e</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/General_Motors" title=3D"Gen=
eral Motors">General Motors</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ord_Motor_Company" title=3D"Ford Motor Company">Ford Motor Company</a>, and=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chrysler" title=3D"Chrysler">Chry=
sler</a> being the world's three largest auto manufacturers for a time, and=
 G.M. and Ford remaining the two largest until the mid-2000s. In 1929, befo=
re the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Great_Depression" title=3D"=
Great Depression">Great Depression</a>, the world had 32,028,500 automobile=
s in use, of which the U.S. automobile enterprises produced more than 90%. =
At that time, the U.S. had one car per 4.87 persons.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Automotive_ind=
ustry#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup> After 1945, the U.S. produced around three-qu=
arters of the world's auto production. In 1980, the U.S. was overtaken by <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Automotive_industry_in_Japan" title=
=3D"Automotive industry in Japan">Japan</a> and then became a world leader =
again in 1994. Japan narrowly passed the U.S. in production during 2006 and=
 2007, and in 2008 also <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Automotive=
_industry_in_China" title=3D"Automotive industry in China">China</a>, which=
 in 2009 took the top spot (from Japan) with 13.8 million units, although t=
he U.S. surpassed Japan in 2011, to become the second-largest automobile in=
dustry. In 2024, China produced more than 31 million vehicles in a year, af=
ter breaking 30 million in 2023, reaching 29 million for the first time in =
2017 and 28 million the year before. In 2024, China produced the most passe=
nger cars in the world, with Japan, India, Germany, and South Korea trailin=
g. This was achieved by Chinese car companies signing joint ventures with f=
oreign manufacturers.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Automotive_industry#cite_note-8"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> =
From 1970 (140 models) to 1998 (260 models) to 2012 (684 models), the numbe=
r of automobile models in the U.S. has grown exponentially.<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-9" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Automot=
ive_industry#cite_note-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
