=3D"white-space:nowrap;">=E2=80=891928</span></figcaption></figure>
<p>In 2007, there were about 806 million cars and light trucks on the road,=
 consuming over 980&nbsp;billion litres (980,000,000&nbsp;m<sup>3</sup>) of=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gasoline" title=3D"Gasoline">gaso=
line</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diesel_fuel" title=3D=
"Diesel fuel">diesel fuel</a> yearly.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-13" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Automotive_industry#cite_not=
e-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup> The automobile is a primary mode of <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transport" title=3D"Transport">transportation</a> for m=
any developed economies. The Detroit branch of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Boston_Consulting_Group" title=3D"Boston Consulting Group">Bos=
ton Consulting Group</a> predicted that, by 2014, one-third of world demand=
 would be in the four <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BRIC_(econom=
ics_term)" title=3D"BRIC (economics term)">BRIC</a> markets (Brazil, Russia=
, India, and China). Meanwhile, in developed countries, the automotive indu=
stry has slowed.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-twnside1_14-0" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Automotive_industry#cite_note-twnside1=
-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup> It is also expected that this trend will continue, especia=
lly as the younger generations of people (in highly urbanized countries) no=
 longer want to own a car, and prefer other modes of transport.<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-15" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Au=
tomotive_industry#cite_note-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Other potentially powerful auto=
motive markets are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iran" title=3D"=
Iran">Iran</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indonesia" titl=
e=3D"Indonesia">Indonesia</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-16" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Automotive_industry#cite_note-16"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup>
Emerging automobile markets already buy more cars than established markets.=
=20
</p><p>According to a J.D. Power study, emerging markets accounted for 51 p=
ercent of the global <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Light_commerc=
ial_vehicle" title=3D"Light commercial vehicle">light-vehicle</a> sales in =
2010. The study, performed in 2010 expected this trend to accelerate.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-17" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Automotive_industry#cite_note-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-18" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Automotive_indus=
try#cite_note-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup> However, more recent reports (2012) confirmed=
 the opposite; namely that the automotive industry was slowing down even in=
 BRIC countries.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-twnside1_14-1" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Automotive_industry#cite_note-twnside1=
-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup> In the United States, vehicle sales peaked in 2000, at 17.=
8 million units.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-19" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Automotive_industry#cite_note-19"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In July 2021, the European Commission released its "<a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/European_Green_Deal" title=3D"European Green Deal"=
>Fit for 55</a>" legislation package,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-20" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Automotive_industry#cite_not=
e-20"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup> which contains important guidelines for the future of the=
 automotive industry; all new cars on the European market must be <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zero-emissions_vehicle" title=3D"Zero-emi=
ssions vehicle">zero-emission vehicles</a> from 2035.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-21=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Automotive_i=
ndustry#cite_note-21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The governments of 24 developed countries and a group of major car m=
anufacturers including <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/General_Mot=
ors" title=3D"General Motors">GM</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Ford_Motor_Company" title=3D"Ford Motor Company">Ford</a>, <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volvo" title=3D"Volvo">Volvo</a>, <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BYD_Auto" title=3D"BYD Auto">BYD Auto</a>, <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jaguar_Land_Rover" title=3D"Jaguar La=
nd Rover">Jaguar Land Rover</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Mercedes-Benz" title=3D"Mercedes-Benz">Mercedes-Benz</a> committed to "wo=
rk towards all sales of new cars and vans being zero emission globally by 2=
040, and by no later than 2035 in leading markets".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-22" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Automotive_ind=
ustry#cite_note-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-23" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Automotive_industry#cite_note-23">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup> Major car manufacturing nations like the United States, Germany=
, China, Japan and South Korea, as well as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Volkswagen" title=3D"Volkswagen">Volkswagen</a>, <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Toyota" title=3D"Toyota">Toyota</a>, <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peugeot" title=3D"Peugeot">Peugeot</a>, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Honda" title=3D"Honda">Honda</a>, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nissan" title=3D"Nissan">Nissan</a> and <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyundai_Motor_Company" title=3D"Hyu=
ndai Motor Company">Hyundai</a>, did not pledge.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-24" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Automotive_indust=
ry#cite_note-24"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Environmental_impacts">Envi=
ronmental impacts</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DAutomotive_industry&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit =
section: Environmental impacts"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:1975-_US_vehicle_production_share,_by_vehicle=
_type.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimed=
ia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/90/1975-_US_vehicle_production_share%2C_by=
_vehicle_type.svg/250px-1975-_US_vehicle_production_share%2C_by_vehicle_typ=
e.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"141" class=3D"mw-file=
-element" data-file-width=3D"1200" data-file-height=3D"675"></a><figcaption=
>Trucks' share of US vehicles produced, has tripled since 1975. Though vehi=
cle fuel efficiency has increased within each category, the overall trend t=
oward less efficient types of vehicles has offset some of the benefits of g=
reater fuel economy and reduction of carbon dioxide emissions.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-EPA_AutomotiveTrends_202212_25-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Automotive_industry#cite_note-EPA_AutomotiveTren=
ds_202212-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>25<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup> Without the shift towards SUVs, energy use per un=
it distance could have fallen 30% more than it did from 2010 to 2022.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-GlobalFuelEfficInit_202311_26-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Automotive_industry#cite_note-GlobalFuelE=
fficInit_202311-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></figcaption></figure>
<p>The global automotive industry is a major consumer of water. Some estima=
tes surpass 180,000&nbsp;L (39,000&nbsp;imp&nbsp;gal) of water per car manu=
factured, depending on whether tyre production is included. Production proc=
esses that use a significant volume of water include surface treatment, pai=
nting, coating, washing, cooling, air-conditioning, and boilers, not counti=
ng component manufacturing. Paintshop operations consume especially large a=
mounts of water because equipment running on water-based products must also=
 be cleaned with water.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-27" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Automotive_industry#cite_note-27"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup>
</p><p>In 2022, Tesla's <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gigafactor=
y_Berlin-Brandenburg" title=3D"Gigafactory Berlin-Brandenburg">Gigafactory =
Berlin-Brandenburg</a> ran into legal challenges due to droughts and fallin=
g groundwater levels in the region. Brandenburg's Economy Minister Joerg St=
einbach said that while water supply was sufficient during the first stage,=
 more would be needed once Tesla expands the site. The factory would nearly=
 double the water consumption in the Gruenheide area, with 1.4 million cubi=
c meters being contracted from local authorities per year =E2=80=94 enough =
for a city of around 40,000 people. Steinbach said that the authorities wou=
ld like to drill for more water there and outsource any additional supply i=
f necessary.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-28" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Automotive_industry#cite_note-28"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>28<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
